JaroCycle 2025-05-10 05:19 a.m.
Your Honor,

The prosecution has made a dramatic and heavily speculative case, but in their eagerness, they’ve ignored the burden of proof and relied instead on implication and association, rather than clear, verifiable facts. Let me walk the Court through why their case is not as "open and shut" as they claim.

Let’s begin with the CCSO parking lot incident. The prosecution claims my client arrived in a vehicle with two felons, NBellantoni and MBellantoni, and implies guilt by association due to a shared surname and alleged gang affiliation. But Your Honor, names do not determine guilt. There is no evidence that my client was engaged in a conspiracy or armed confrontation with those individuals. The prosecution admits they “don’t know” who drove or who was involved in the shooting. That level of uncertainty alone undermines their entire premise. Simply being present in a public place or sharing a vehicle—something my client have not admitted to nor has been conclusively proven—does not violate probation unless it’s shown that my client knowingly and willingly associated with those individuals with felonious intent. No such intent has been demonstrated here.

As for the so-called “threatening” message to the Probation Officer—“you don’t want this” followed by “believe me”—those phrases, taken out of context and twisted to fit a narrative, are not a clear-cut threat. The prosecution admits that it is “not a clear violation” and relies on “interpretation.” Probation violations must be proven by substantial evidence, not by subjective fear or vague interpretations. If every ambiguous message were criminalized, we'd all be in violation of something.
JaroCycle 2025-05-10 05:19 a.m.
Moving on to the arrest involving the Coin-O-Matic van. The report states that my client was a passenger, not the driver or instigator. Being in a vehicle does not make my client criminally liable for the actions of others unless there is clear evidence of my participation in or knowledge of a crime taking place. None was provided.

Your Honor, this is not justice—it is guilt by association, and assumption presented as evidence. I ask that you consider the actual facts, not the emotion. The prosecution’s argument stretches those past actions of my client into a narrative they have failed to conclusively prove.

meowiitten 2025-05-10 05:06 p.m.
PAPERLESS DECISION AND ORDER: Criminal contempt is punishable by fine or imprisonment, or both, at the discretion of the court. 5 M.S.C. 1 § 2104.1. The contempt statute permits this punishment to curtail “misbehavior in the presence of the court or near thereto obstructing the administration of justice,” “misbehavior by an officer of the court in officials transactions,” and “disobedience to a lawful… command.” 1 M.S.C. § 1501; accord 5 M.S.C. 1 § 2104.1. Based on the arguments of counsel and the record herein, the Court finds that the defendant's conduct satisfies the elements of criminal contempt beyond a reasonable doubt. Therefore, it is hereby ORDERED that the defendant shall serve 180 minutes of imprisonment. District Judge sadoimpacto (Entered: 05/10/2025)
